Gases at atmospheric conditions are usually liquified by compressing (which heats it up and reduces its volume), cooling it back down (but keeping the higher pressure (,repeat as often as desired) and then expanding it through a nozzle. If done appropriately parts of the expanding gas should then start condensing as a liquid. The remaining non-condensed cold gas gets sent back into the feed stream and goes through the whole process again.
The liquified gas should then remain at its respective boiling temperature at that pressure and bubble away.
Those boiling temperatures can be silly low, or even unachievable at atmospheric pressure.

The Space Shuttle Main Engine was also closed-cycle with 2 turbopumps, designed in the early 1970's, with leftovers used in the new SLS vehicle.  But both preburners ran fuel-rich, whereas SpaceX Raptor runs one turbopump oxygen-rich (more efficient).  In the 1960's, U.S. engineers thought running Ox-rich would be impossible in a metal chamber, as every welder knows one switches a gas torch to pure oxygen to cut thru steel.  But, surprisingly the Soviets did that in their NK-33 engine for their Moon program.  Their trick was to use copper in the preburner and a materials trick for the steel alloy turbine blades.  Leftover NK-33 engines were later used in ULA's Taurus vehicle in the 2000's.  The U.S. IPD demo engine of the early 2000's also had an ox-rich preburner, so by the time of SpaceX Raptor design, there were at least 2 prior liquid engines which had proven an ox-rich preburner.
